---
terminal_stack:
  shell: zsh                          # bash, fish, nushell
  terminal: ghostty                   # kitty, alacritty, wezterm, iterm2
  multiplexer: tmux                   # zellij, screen, none
  session_manager: sesh               # tmuxinator, tmuxp, none
  env_manager: mise                   # direnv, none
  version_manager: mise               # asdf, nvm, pyenv, rbenv
  secret_store: keychainctl           # 1password-cli, bitwarden-cli, pass
  package_managers: [homebrew, uv, npm]

preferences:
  default_task_runner: mise           # make, just, task
  function_location: ~/.zsh/functions
  mise_task_style: included_files     # included_files | inline | toml_tasks
  credential_pattern: multi_tenant    # multi_tenant | single_env | keychain_only

versions:
  mise: ""
  tmux: ""
  sesh: ""
  zsh: ""

workflow_patterns:
  # Populated by agent during sessions or via /workflow-discover
  # Each entry tracks a repeated command sequence and its graduation status.
  #
  # example_pattern:
  #   commands: ["git pull", "mise run lint", "mise run test"]
  #   frequency: 12
  #   suggested_graduation: "mise_task"    # function | mise_task | sesh_template
  #   status: observed                     # observed | suggested | graduated

tool_preferences:
  # Frecency data from /workflow-discover history analysis.
  # Tracks which tools the user actively uses and what for.
  #
  # fzf:
  #   use_count: 87
  #   last_used: "2026-05-01"
  #   preferred_for: ["branch selection", "file search"]
---

## Notes

Terminal stack profile for terminal-guru. The agent reads this to tailor advice
without re-asking about the user's setup. Update versions and preferences as
they change.

Copy this file to create your profile:
  cp .terminal-guru-profile.local.md.example .terminal-guru-profile.local.md

Or place it in XDG config for visibility:
  mkdir -p ${XDG_CONFIG_HOME:-~/.config}/terminal-guru
  cp .terminal-guru-profile.local.md.example ${XDG_CONFIG_HOME:-~/.config}/terminal-guru/profile.md

Metrics and patterns only — secrets belong in keychainctl or your secret store.
